  "prompt": "Is Hinduism monotheistic or polytheistic?",
  "response": "Hinduism is often described as both monotheistic and polytheistic, as it encompasses a wide range of beliefs and practices. \n\n1. **Polytheism**: Hinduism includes a rich pantheon of gods and goddesses, such as Brahma, Vishnu, Shiva, Lakshmi, Saraswati, and many others. Devotees may worship various deities based on regional beliefs, personal preferences, and specific traditions.\n\n2. **Monotheism**: Many Hindus also believe in a single, supreme reality known as Brahman, which is formless and transcends individual deities. Some schools of Hindu philosophy emphasize monism or the idea that all forms of existence are manifestations of this one ultimate reality. \n\n3. **Henotheism**: Some describe Hinduism as henotheistic, meaning that while there are many gods, a devotee may choose to worship one particular deity as the supreme being without denying the existence of others.\n\nOverall, Hinduism is a complex and pluralistic faith that allows for a variety of interpretations and practices regarding the divine.",
